### History

The island’s narrative is less a story of organic growth and more a meticulously crafted resort for the obscenely wealthy.

#### Native beginnings

Before the gilded age descended, the [Jaega](/Jaega) people, for at least 3,000 years, called this island home. Their presence is marked by archaeological remnants – burial mounds, cemeteries, and sites hinting at early interactions with Europeans. A stark contrast to the opulent structures that would later dominate the landscape.

#### 1872–1900

The trickle of white settlers began around 1872. Hiram F. Hammon staked a claim in 1873. By 1877, a post office, Tustenegee, appeared. Then came the Providencia, a ship that met its end in 1878, conveniently shedding 20,000 coconuts along the coast. These, naturally, took root. In 1880, [Elisha Newton "Cap" Dimick](/Elisha_Newton_Dimick) opened the Cocoanut Grove House, the sole hotel between [Titusville](/Titusville,_Florida) and [Key West](/Key_West) at the time. A fire claimed it in 1893. The legendary [Barefoot Mailman](/Barefoot_Mailman) route, a 136-mile trek by foot and boat, began serving the area in 1885. The first schoolhouse, a "Little Red Schoolhouse," opened its doors in 1886.

Then, [Henry Flagler](/Henry_Flagler), the Standard Oil titan, arrived in 1893. He declared the place a "veritable paradise." His vision was less about paradise and more about profit and exclusivity. He commissioned the plotting of [West Palm Beach](/West_Palm_Beach,_Florida) to house the workers for his grand hotels. The [Royal Poinciana Hotel](/Royal_Poinciana_Hotel) opened in 1894, followed by [The Breakers](/The_Breakers_(hotel)) in 1896. The [Florida East Coast Railway](/Florida_East_Coast_Railway) was extended south, a lifeline for his opulent empire. The [Palm Beach Daily News](/Palm_Beach_Daily_News), originally the Daily Lake Worth News, began its publication in 1897, chronicling the gilded existence.

#### 1900–1940

The early 20th century saw Palm Beach solidify its status. A pedestrian bridge, a precursor to the Flagler Bridge, spanned the Intracoastal in 1901. Flagler himself built his [Beaux-Arts](/Beaux-Arts_architecture) mansion, [Whitehall](/Flagler_Museum), designed by [Carrère and Hastings](/Carr%C3%A8re_and_Hastings), in 1902, cementing the island’s reputation as *the* winter destination for the elite. Telephone service arrived in 1908.

The town's history is also marked by displacement. Prior to the 1910s, African Americans resided in a segregated area known as the "Styx." Between 1910 and 1912, they were forcibly evicted, relocating to neighborhoods in West Palm Beach.

In 1911, facing annexation by West Palm Beach, residents rallied. Dimick, [Louis Semple Clarke](/Louis_Semple_Clarke), and others incorporated the Town of Palm Beach on April 17, 1911. Dimick became the first mayor. The [Royal Park Bridge](/Royal_Park_Bridge) was built that same year, initially a wooden structure, charging tolls for passage.

The architect [Addison Mizner](/Addison_Mizner) left an indelible, albeit often gaudy, mark between 1919 and 1924, designing 67 structures. His clients read like a who's who of the era's wealthy and influential. His work included [El Mirasol](/El_Mirasol_(mansion)), the [Everglades Club](/Everglades_Club), [La Querida](/La_Querida_(mansion)), and [Via Mizner](/Via_Mizner), which became the genesis of [Worth Avenue](/Worth_Avenue)'s retail landscape.

The [Palm Beach Town Hall](/Palm_Beach_Town_Hall), designed by Harvey and Clarke, was completed in 1925, a monument to civic pride and, no doubt, expense. The [Florida land boom](/Florida_land_boom_of_the_1920s) fueled construction, with revenues reaching $14 million in 1925. Then came the [1928 Okeechobee hurricane](/1928_Okeechobee_hurricane), a brutal reminder of nature’s indifference to wealth, inflicting $10 million in damage.

#### 1940–1960

Palm Beach saw its population more than double between 1930 and 1940, reaching 3,747. The grand Royal Poinciana Hotel, a victim of the Depression and the 1928 hurricane, was demolished in 1935. The [Society of the Four Arts](/Society_of_the_Four_Arts) was founded in 1936. The Flagler Memorial Bridge, completed in 1938, further connected the island to the mainland.

During [World War II](/World_War_II), the island, like much of the coast, was militarized. A Ranger camp was established. Blackouts were enforced. German U-boats prowled offshore. The Breakers became a hospital, and the Palm Beach Biltmore Hotel, a U.S. Naval Special Hospital and training facility for the [SPARS](/SPARS).

The Southern Boulevard Bridge opened in 1950, the third connection to the mainland. Palm Beach elected its only native-born mayor, Claude Dimick Reese, in 1953. The town’s population continued its steady climb, reaching 6,055 by 1960.

#### 1960–1990

The Kennedys cast a long shadow over Palm Beach. [John F. Kennedy](/John_F._Kennedy), during his presidency, used [La Querida](/La_Querida_(mansion)) as his [Winter White House](/List_of_residences_of_presidents_of_the_United_States). The town's police averted an assassination attempt on him in 1960. He spent his final weekend there before his death in 1963.

Yvelyne "Deedy" Marix shattered a glass ceiling in 1970, becoming the first woman elected to the town council, and later, in 1983, the first female mayor. [Earl E.T. Smith](/Earl_E.T._Smith), former [Ambassador of the United States to Cuba](/Ambassador_of_the_United_States_to_Cuba), served as mayor from 1971 to 1977.

In 1974, Barbara Hoffstot’s book, *Landmark Architecture in Palm Beach*, highlighted the need for historic preservation. This led to the establishment of the Landmarks Preservation Commission in 1979.

[Marjorie Merriweather Post](/Marjorie_Merriweather_Post), heiress to [General Foods](/General_Foods) and [Post Cereals](/Post_Consumer_Brands), bequeathed [Mar-a-Lago](/Mar-a-Lago) to the nation in 1973, envisioning it as a presidential retreat. It eventually returned to the family and was purchased by [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump) in 1985. He transformed it into a club and, later, his own version of a Winter White House. A [nor'easter](/Late_November_1984_nor%27easter) in 1984 brought the ill-fated yacht Mercedes I crashing into a seawall, providing a brief, dramatic spectacle.

#### 1990–2010

The infamous [1991 Perfect Storm](/1991_Perfect_Storm) battered the coast, destroying seawalls and causing [coastal flooding](/Coastal_flooding). The trial of [William Kennedy Smith](/William_Kennedy_Smith) in 1991, accused of rape at La Querida, captivated the international media, ending in acquittal. [Paul Ilyinsky](/Paul_Ilyinsky), son of [Grand Duke Dmitri Pavlovich of Russia](/Grand_Duke_Dmitri_Pavlovich_of_Russia) and [Audrey Emery](/Audrey_Emery), served as mayor starting in 1993.

Palm Beach reached its population peak of 10,468 in the 2000 census. The town’s police department, under Chief [Michael Reiter](/Michael_Reiter_(police_officer)), initiated the investigation into [Jeffrey Epstein](/Jeffrey_Epstein) in 2005, a case that would expose a network of exploitation and result in a controversially lenient plea deal for Epstein in 2008.

#### 2010–present

By 2010, the population had dipped to 8,348, a significant decrease. The town celebrated its centennial in 2011. The Town Square underwent a $5.7 million restoration.

In August 2022, the FBI executed a search warrant at [Mar-a-Lago](/Mar-a-Lago) related to classified documents. This led to a federal indictment against Donald Trump in June 2023 for mishandling those documents.

### Name

The town's name, Palm Beach, is attributed to the wreck of the *Providencia* in January 1878. The ship, carrying coconuts from [Havana](/Havana,_Cuba) to [Cádiz, Spain](/C%C3%A1diz,_Spain), foundered near the coast. The cargo washed ashore, and the resulting proliferation of palm trees gave the island its distinctive moniker.

### Geography

Palm Beach is an 18-mile-long [barrier island](/Barrier_island), never exceeding three-quarters of a mile in width. It’s a delicate strip of land, separating the [Intracoastal Waterway](/Intracoastal_Waterway) (or [Lake Worth Lagoon](/Lake_Worth_Lagoon), as it’s locally known) from the Atlantic Ocean. The town's northern edge meets the Lake Worth Inlet, and its southern boundary extends to the edge of [South Palm Beach](/South_Palm_Beach,_Florida).

The island is essentially a sand-covered ridge of [coquina rock](/Coquina_rock). Historically, the western side was marshy, but development has drastically altered the environment, filling sloughs and reshaping the coastline. The Atlantic ridge remains the dominant feature, acting as a natural, albeit vulnerable, seawall.

The town, along with the entire barrier island, falls within Evacuation Zone B, a stark reminder of its susceptibility to the region’s powerful storms.

Land use is overwhelmingly residential (60%), with a significant portion dedicated to [rights-of-way](/Right_of_way_(property_access)) (13%) and private recreational uses. The town is essentially built out, with no room for expansion. Conservation efforts are limited to a few small islands designated as bird sanctuaries.

### Climate

Palm Beach boasts a [tropical rainforest climate](/Tropical_rainforest_climate) (Af), characterized by hot, humid summers and warm, drier winters. Annual rainfall hovers around 62.3 inches (1,580 mm), with the bulk falling between May and October. Afternoon thunderstorms are a summer staple, offering brief respite from the heat. While tropical cyclones are a threat, direct hits are infrequent, the last significant one being the [1928 Okeechobee hurricane](/1928_Okeechobee_hurricane).

Summers are generally hot and humid, with average highs ranging from 83 to 91 °F (28 to 33 °C). Winters are mild and pleasant, with highs between 74 and 82 °F (23 to 28 °C) and lows typically between 57 and 68 °F (14 to 20 °C). The record high is a scorching 101 °F (38 °C), while the lowest recorded temperature was a frigid 24 °F (−4 °C) during the [Great Freeze](/Great_Freeze) of 1894.

